    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1038_s41467_023_39889_1__task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The research question frames the task as reproducing asari on a 'publicly deposited' dataset, but the paper does not discuss public dataset deposition or reproducibility on external datasets\u2014it only benchmarks asari on internal datasets (HZV029, Yeast2021, BM21, E. coli, SLAW, NIST SRM 1950).",
        "The expected outputs list five specific filenames with precise naming conventions (preferred_Feature_table.tsv, _mass_grid_mapping.csv, cmap.pickle, epd.pickle, Annotated_empiricalCompounds.json). The paper does not document these exact filenames or confirm all five are produced as standard outputs.",
        "The tools list includes several low-level scipy functions (scipy.signal.find_peaks, scipy.signal.detrend) and databases (JMS, HMDB 4) that are not mentioned in the paper. The paper describes algorithmic concepts (local maximum search, detrending, baseline estimation) but does not name the specific scipy functions or external databases used."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:42:43.450455+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1038_s41467_023_39889_1__task_002/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "With this approach, elution peak detection is no longer required on individual samples. It can be done on the composite mass track, then the peak area is looked up in each individual sample and reported as feature intensity values (Fig. 2b). This greatly simplifies feature correspondence, and has a significant performance gain, by not repeating the computational cost of peak detection on all individual samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Research question directly supported by paper's core design principle and performance claims.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does performing peak detection on a single composite map rather than on individual samples improve computational efficiency in metabolomics data processing?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:43:08.802324+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1038_s41467_023_39889_1__task_002/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A mass track is defined as a series of LC-MS data points of the same consensus m/z value and spanning the full retention time (Supplementary Fig. 1)... In asari, aligned mass tracks are summed into a 'composite mass track' after correction of retention time (Fig. 2b).",
      "asbval:note": "Composite mass tracks with consensus m/z and full RT span explicitly described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Composite mass tracks (summed intensity arrays) indexed by consensus m/z and full RT scan length",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:43:08.802324+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1038_s41467_023_39889_1__task_002/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The detected peaks are assessed by a set of quality metrics and retained only if the preset thresholds are met... SNR (signal-to-noise ratio) is often defined differently among tools. In asari, the noise for an elution peak is the average signal intensity of neighboring non-peak data points, 100 to each side; SNR is the ratio between peak height and noise (Fig. 6a)... cSelectivity is defined as how distinct chromatograhic elution peaks are (Fig. 6b). Together with peak shape, users can rely on them to routinely determine the peak quality... These quality metrics are exported with the feature tables in asari.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms peak area, height, SNR, cSelectivity, and peak shape (goodness_fitting) are exported. Baseline boundaries and parent_masstrack_id linkage are mentioned conceptually (Fig. 2c describes explicit linking) but not explicitly detailed in passages provided. Partial support due to incomplete specification of all output fields.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "expected_outputs",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Feature list with detected elution peaks on composite tracks: peak apex (scan), peak area, height, baseline boundaries, cSelectivity, SNR, goodness_fitting, and parent_masstrack_id",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:43:08.802324+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_1038_s41467_023_39889_1__task_002/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "With this approach, elution peak detection is no longer required on individual samples. It can be done on the composite mass track, then the peak area is looked up in each individual sample and reported as feature intensity values (Fig. 2b). This greatly simplifies feature correspondence, and has a significant performance gain, by not repeating the computational cost of peak detection on all individual samples.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly contrasts single composite-map detection vs. per-sample detection and emphasizes computational savings from avoiding N passes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_002",
