    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Requires Python 3.8+.",
      "asbval:note": "Explicitly stated in the candidate card's evidence_spans and confirmed in passage metadata.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Python 3.8+",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:48:33.891416+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For MZmine and MS-DIAL, processing 100 samples often becomes challenging on a desktop computer. XCMS is considered more performant and is the default choice of cloud computing. Here, the computational efficiency of asari is benchmarked against XCMS using multiple datasets of different sizes and platforms. Small studies can be processed by asari under a minute. Some studies of 100 ~ 200 samples take less than 10 min by asari using a single CPU core. Therefore, asari provides significant improvement of CPU time over XCMS by 1 ~ 2 orders of magnitude.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates computational scalability improvements and addresses the bottleneck of repeated peak detection across samples. The specific threshold numbers (>10 samples, >1000 m/z) are not explicitly stated but are consistent with the paper's scope.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When processing aligned LC-MS data across multiple samples where the computational bottleneck is repeated peak-detection algorithm calls (one per sample per m/z value). Typical scenario: >10 samples with >1000 m/z values each, where N individual find_peaks invocations dominate ru",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:48:33.891416+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection/010",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Retention time (RT) correction between samples, also called retention time alignment, is carried out by LOWESS regression, using a small subset of high-quality elution peaks. These reference peaks are easy to select from previously aligned mass tracks, preferably as the only peak on a mass track.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms RT alignment via LOWESS regression is a prerequisite for composite construction, but does not explicitly mention 'rt_cal_dict' data structure name or the specific intensity threshold of 1e3. The functional requirement is present but the specific parameter name and threshold value are not verified.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "computational-efficiency-single-pass-vs-repeated-detection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Particularly valuable when samples are aligned to a common retention-time reference via rt_cal_dict calibration dictionaries and when composite signal is strong enough to enable robust peak detection (median intensity >1e3).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:48:33.891416+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/computational-resource-profiling-and-benchmarking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To test the scalability, we subset the SLAW data using varying sample numbers. The CPU time and memory use was largely a linear function of sample numbers (Fig. 8b, c). The results indicate that the performance gap between XCMS and asari widens for larger studies.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly benchmarks asari's wall-clock time and memory across varying sample counts (Fig. 8b, c) to verify scalability.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "computational-resource-profiling-and-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Systematically measure and characterize wall-clock runtime and peak memory consumption of a metabolomics processing tool across increasing sample cohort sizes to verify scalability claims and establish throughput benchmarks on target hardware.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:48:54.591067+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/computational-resource-profiling-and-benchmarking/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we develop the open-source software tool asari for LC-MS metabolomics data processing. Asari is designed with a set of specific algorithmic framework and data structures, and all steps are explicitly trackable. Asari compares favorably to other tools in feature detection and quantification. It offers substantial improvement in computational performance over current tools, and it is highly scalable.",
      "asbval:note": "asari is the primary subject of performance benchmarking in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "computational-resource-profiling-and-benchmarking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "asari \u2014 Target tool being profiled for scalability across increasing sample counts",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:48:54.591067+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
