    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-across-samples/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A mass track is defined as a series of LC-MS data points of the same consensus m/z value and spanning the full retention time... Mass tracks are aligned cross samples before elution peak detection in asari (Fig. 2a, right)... Aligned mass tracks of all samples form a 'MassGrid', which provides a foundation for trackable and high-quality feature correspondence.",
      "asbval:note": "Scope description aligns with paper's description of mass track alignment workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-across-samples",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After mass track construction for individual samples, when you need to establish consensus m/z values across a cohort of LC-MS samples to build a unified feature table.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:21.188333+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-across-samples/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The mass tracks that match 13 C/12 C and Na/H patterns are considered of high confidence and used as guides in the m/z alignment.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed that anchor mass tracks (13C/12C and Na/H) are used as guides in alignment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-across-samples",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill when sample count is known and you have extracted mass tracks with identified anchor mass tracks (13C/12C isotopes or Na/H adducts) for each sample.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:21.188333+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-across-samples/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "A feature in LC-MS metabolomics is defined by a unique pair of m/z value and retention time in chromatography. The m/z value of a peak is first determined per sample. When peaks are later aligned cross samples (i.e., correspondence), the m/z values vary slightly in each sample and the algorithm must ensure the correct peaks are grouped and report a consensus m/z value.",
      "asbval:note": "Scope correctly identifies that alignment is not needed if consensus m/z already exists.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-across-samples",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input is already a feature table or consensus m/z list (alignment already performed).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:21.188333+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-across-samples/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Asari takes centroid mzML files as input and builds chromatograms for each as mass tracks. To prioritize modern mass resolution, m/z alignment is performed first to form a MassGrid, aided by isotopic landmarks.",
      "asbval:note": "Confirmed that mass track extraction precedes alignment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-across-samples",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Mass tracks have not yet been extracted or anchor mass tracks have not been identified.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:21.188333+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Mass tracks are aligned cross samples before elution peak detection in asari (Fig. 2a, right). This takes advantage of the superb mass resolution on today's instruments and avoids errors stemming from elution peak detection. Mass tracks lock in unique m/z values per sample, therefore greatly reducing the complexity of m/z alignment, compared to the alignment of individual elution peaks... Aligned mass tracks of all samples form a 'MassGrid', which provides a foundation for trackable and high-quality feature correspondence.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes m/z alignment and MassGrid construction, but does NOT mention 'hierarchical clustering' as the alignment method. The paper describes mass track alignment using isotopic landmarks and mass resolution-based grouping, but the specific clustering algorithm is not named as 'hierarchical clustering' in the passages provided.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Aligns mass tracks (extracted ion chromatograms) across multiple LC-MS samples using high-mass-resolution m/z separation and hierarchical clustering to build a unified MassGrid that serves as the foundation for composite peak detection and feature extraction.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Mass alignment should not be conditioned on elution peak detection in high resolution metabolomics... Here, m/z alignment occurs after detection of elution peaks in each sample... We note that the construction of chromatograms is straight forward in high resolution data, but detection of elution peaks is very error prone... Without tracking EICs explicitly, it is a poor design to perform m/z alignment after elution peak detection. [asari] takes centroid mzML files as input and builds chromatograms for each as mass tracks. To prioritize modern mass resolution, m/z alignment is performed first to form a MassGrid, aided by isotopic landmarks.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states asari prioritizes mass resolution by performing m/z alignment first, before elution peak detection.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill prioritizes mass resolution over retention time to handle co-eluting isomers and complex mixtures.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Asari takes centroid mzML files as input and builds chromatograms for each as mass tracks. To prioritize modern mass resolution, m/z alignment is performed first to form a MassGrid, aided by isotopic landmarks. Aligned mass tracks across samples are corrected for RT, using LOWESS regression on a subset of high-quality elution peaks, then aggregated into composite mass tracks... Elution peak detection is performed on the composite mass tracks, and feature table is generated by looking up the corresponding peak areas in each individual sample.",
      "asbval:note": "Workflow order is confirmed: mass tracks \u2192 m/z alignment \u2192 MassGrid \u2192 composite mass tracks \u2192 peak detection.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill after mass track extraction (binning and clustering within individual samples) but before composite peak detection.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Metabolomics today usually employs high-resolution mass spectrometers that are often capable of mass resolution at 5 ppm (part per million) or better... To take advantage of the mass resolution in current data, mass alignment is performed first, represented by mass tracks within and composite mass tracks across acquisitions in an LC-MS metabolomics experiment.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper mentions 5 ppm as standard mass resolution but does NOT explicitly describe 'pairwise anchor-first mode' for \u226410 samples vs 'centroiding mode' for larger cohorts. The specific sample-size-stratified algorithm selection is not detailed in the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Essential when sample cohort is \u226410 samples (pairwise anchor-first mode) or larger (centroiding mode), and when mass resolution is \u22655 ppm tolerance or better.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The goal of data processing is to report a quantitative value per metabolite feature per sample, which is a proxy for its biological concentration... feature table is generated by looking up the corresponding peak areas in each individual sample.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms feature tables are the output of the pipeline, not input to m/z alignment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input is already a feature table (preferred_Feature_table.tsv or full_Feature_table.tsv); alignment has already been performed.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Asari takes centroid mzML files as input and builds chromatograms for each as mass tracks... Centroiding is supported by all major instrument manufacturers. Tools like ThermoRawFileParser and msConvert are commonly used both for data format conversion and for centroiding.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states asari requires centroided mzML input, not raw profile-mode data.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Raw (profile-mode) mzML data; asari requires centroided input to define discrete m/z b",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:50:39.025855+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we develop the open-source software tool asari for LC-MS metabolomics data processing. Asari is designed with a set of specific algorithmic framework and data structures, and all steps are explicitly trackable... Aligned mass tracks of all samples form a 'MassGrid', which provides a foundation for trackable and high-quality feature correspondence.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms asari implements MassGrid construction and mass track alignment, but does NOT name the specific internal function names (MassGrid.build_grid_sample_wise, etc.) in the passages provided. These appear to be implementation details not documented in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "m-z-alignment-and-mass-grid-assembly",
