    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/quality-control-metric-distribution-analysis/009",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "XCMS and asari used similar parameters (peak height > 1E5)... asari, which, by default, does not return peaks of bad shapes (under 0.5)... For each feature, the retention time was padded 3 s on each side of peak boundary, to accommodate processing variations. The redundant features (within 5 ppm and 6 s) were first grouped in XCMS and MZmine results. Thus, the total feature numbers in this analysis are 5809 for XCMS, 10876 for MZmine (wavelets), and 14394 for MZmine (local minimum). The MZmine (wavelets) result has 6841 good peaks and 4035 bad peaks.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms peak_height > 1E5 and peak shape > 0.5 thresholds. SNR > 2 and 20% prominence thresholds are not explicitly stated in passages; prominence is discussed qualitatively but no specific percentage is given.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "quality-control-metric-distribution-analysis",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "baseline thresholds (SNR > 2, goodness_fitting > 0.5, peak_height \u2265 1e5 with \u226520% prominence)",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:54:05.757661+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-alignment-index-mapping/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Retention time (RT) correction between samples, also called retention time alignment, is carried out by LOWESS regression, using a small subset of high-quality elution peaks. These reference peaks are easy to select from previously aligned mass tracks, preferably as the only peak on a mass track. The regression result is translated to an RT remapping function for each sample.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes RT alignment via LOWESS regression producing RT remapping functions (equivalent to calibration dictionaries) that map sample coordinates to reference coordinates for composite mass track construction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-alignment-index-mapping",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Maps scan numbers across LC-MS samples to a reference retention-time coordinate system using sample-specific calibration dictionaries, enabling synchronized intensity summation across aligned mass tracks for downstream composite peak detection.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:54:27.783753+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-alignment-index-mapping/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Aligned mass tracks across samples are corrected for RT, using LOWESS regression on a subset of high-quality elution peaks, then aggregated into composite mass tracks. Elution peak detection is performed on the composite mass tracks, and feature table is generated by looking up the corresponding peak areas in each individual sample.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states RT correction precedes composite mass track aggregation and peak detection.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-alignment-index-mapping",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This step is critical for accurate composite-map construction when samples have different scan acquisition patterns or retention-time drift.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:54:27.783753+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/retention-time-alignment-index-mapping/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Retention time (RT) correction between samples, also called retention time alignment, is carried out by LOWESS regression, using a small subset of high-quality elution peaks.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms LOWESS regression is used for RT alignment with high-quality elution peaks as anchors, but does not name the specific function 'rt_lowess_calibration'. The functional role is confirmed; the exact module/function name cannot be verified from passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41467-023-39889-1",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "retention-time-alignment-index-mapping",
